      <h2>Web security. Are you safe?</h2>
	  <h3>From the text, there are six properties that will show
	  how much info anyone, including this website, can get on you!</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>onLine</li>
				<ul>
					<li>This can tell if you are connected to a network connection or not.</li>
				</ul>
			<li>appName</li>
				<ul>
					<li>This can tell the name of your web browser you are using to look at the page.</li>
					</ul>
			<li>appVersion</li>
				<ul>
					<li>This tells what version of your web broswer you are using to display the page.</li>
					</ul>
			<li>geolocation</li>
				<ul>
					<li>This one is really scary because it can tell where you are at, assuming you are not obfuscating your whereabouts with a VPN or something like that.</li>
					</ul>
			<li>platform</li>
				<ul>
					<li>This tells what operating system you are using.</li>
					</ul>
			<li>userAgent</li>
				<ul>
					<li>This stores in the HTTP user-agent request header information on your browser, platform name like your OS, and compatability.</li>
				</ul>
			</ul>
		<h3>What does all this mean though?</h3>
		<p>To be blunt, it means a lot. Here is why, most of that information can help a 
		hacker know what tools to use to attack your system. It can also help them
		identify ways to social engineer you so you will download a virus that gives
		them control of your system. There are many exploits out there that don't even 
		require you to have a virus. They are called exploits and they allow a hacker 
		to gain access to your system, and the operators I just listed allow them to 
		figure out which one of those exploits to use. It even tells them what version
		you are using so they can fine-tune the attack.</p>
		<p>Following are some articles about exploits and some of the practices to shore up your defenses against attacks:</p>
